LATEST STORIES


   NEW Spanish LanguageVersion of Amesnews
   January 29 Students Can Search For A Habitable Planet on New NASA
   Website
   Astroferret Searching for a fictional planet on which people could live
   is one of the student activities available on a new NASA website that
   will open for business on Feb.1 at: http://astroventure.arc.nasa.gov.
   Astro ferret, a cartoon character, will guide students through a
   series of role-playing steps on the multi-media, interactive website.
   Young people using the 'Astro-venture' website can observe the effects
   of changes to the Earth and draw conclusions about what is needed for
   survival. Participants can feel that they are part of an Internet
   world by receiving information seamlessly, through use of graphics,
   audio, video and audio transcriptions.
   Full Story | En Español
   January 24

   10,000 Students To Attend Frozen Worlds Project At NASA Ames
   students Some 10,000 students from the greater San Francisco Bay area
   will interact via satellite with scientists in Alaska during 50
   telecasts Jan. 28 - Feb. 8 at NASA's Ames Research Center in
   California's Silicon Valley. During the broadcasts, local students from
   grades 3 to 12 can talk live by satellite with scientists and students
   in polar regions who are studying geology, climate change, native
   cultures, plants, animals and even the bacteria of some of Earth's
   colder places. These investigations are part of "JASON Project XIII:
   Frozen Worlds." Organizers intend to show students connections between
   science concepts and real-world problems. Students also will take part
   in many hands-on educational activities in historic Hangar 1 at Ames.
   Full Story
   January 23

   NASA Kids' Web Site 'En Espanol '
   web kids Professor image NASA's popular educational Web site, Space
   Place, has announced a new Spanish-language version for children and
   their families. The Web site at http://spaceplace.nasa.gov and its new
   Spanish companion at http://spaceplace.nasa.gov/espanol serve children
   8 to 13 years of age. The site contains approximately 40 activities,
   including games and "amazing facts" about space, Earth and NASA. The
   2000 census data shows that Spanish is the primary language for more
   than 27 million people living in the U.S. Of those, nearly 13 million
   feel they do not speak English very well.
   Full Story | En Español

